rt","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Cheshire): habitational name from a place in Cheshire named Davenport, from the Dane river (apparently named with a Celtic cognate of Middle Welsh <i>dafnu</i> ‘to drop, to trickle’) + Old English <i>port</i> ‘market town’.","Irish: in Tipperary, this is an English surname adopted by bearers of Munster Gaelic <b>Ó Donndubhartaigh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Donndubhartach</i>’, a personal name composed of the elements <i>donn</i> ‘brown-haired man’ or ‘chieftain’ + <i>dubh</i> ‘black’ + <i>artach</i> ‘nobleman’.","History: John Davenport (died 1670) arrived in Boston, MA, in 1637. He came of an English Cheshire family associated with Capesthorne Hall, near Macclesfield."],"variants":[{"name":"Devenport","meanings":["English and Irish (Lancashire): variant of   Davenport  . The spelling <b>Devonport</b> is found in Ireland and it may have been this form which gave rise to <i>Devenport</i>."]},{"name":"Dunworth","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Eamon, Niall.","Irish: adopted in Ireland by bearers of Gaelic <b>Ó Donndubhartaigh</b> (see   Davenport   2).","English: perhaps a variant of <b>Dungworth</b>, see   Dunsworth  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"John Davenport was born about 1281 as the son of Sir Thomas Davenport and Elizabeth. He had at least 1 son with Alice de Bromehall."},"et":{"about 1281–":"umbes 1281–Surnud","1281–Male":"1281–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1365–1436":"1365–1436","–Male":"Surnud","1436":"1436","about 1281":"umbes 1281","1365